`cursor.getColumnIndex(...)` only returns the column index for the row. To get the value in that column, you have a few options:

- If you know the data type in advance, you can directly call the corresponding method on the `cursor`. For example, if the column `DBHelper.KEY_NAME` contains a `String`, we can query the value in that column directly using `cursor.getString(cursor.getColumnIndex(DBHelper.KEY_NAME))`

- If you don&#39;t, you can try calling [`cursor.getType(int columnIndex)`](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html#getType(int)) to get the underlying type, then call the appropriate method on the cursor based on the returned value.

In short, the issue with your code is that you are getting the column _indices_ (`getColumnIndex`) instead of the column _values_ (`getFloat`, `getInt`, `getString` etc.):

```Java
    ...
    int idIndex = cursor.getColumnIndex(DBHelper.KEY_ID);
    int nameIndex = cursor.getColumnIndex(DBHelper.KEY_NAME);
    int hourIndex = cursor.getColumnIndex(DBHelper.KEY_HOUR);
    int dateIndex = cursor.getColumnIndex(DBHelper.KEY_DATE);
    String name = cursor.getString(nameIndex);
    String hour = cursor.getString(hourIndex);
    String date = cursor.getString(dateIndex);
  ...
```

